AU  - McIntosh, Craig
AU  - Woodruff, Christopher
T1  - What Are the Headwaters of Formal Savings? Experimental Evidence from Sri Lanka
PY  - 2019
Y1  - 2019/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdz020
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 86
IS  - 6
SP  - 2491
EP  - 2529
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The world’s poor are seeing a rapid expansion in access to formal savings accounts. What is the source of savings when households are connected to a formal account? We combine a high-frequency panel survey spanning two and a half years with an experiment in which a Sri Lankan bank used mobile Point-of-Service (POS) terminals to collect deposits directly from households each week. We find that the headwaters of formal savings lie in sacrificed leisure time: households work more, and improved savings options generate an increase in labour effort in both self-employment and in the wage market. The results suggest that the labour allocation channel is an important mechanism linking savings opportunities to income.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdz020
ER  - 



